																		<p>
																			Some of the fonts we use have cost hundreds of pounds, and we pay that because we know the time and effort went into creating them and the value they give in making your invitations look exquisite. </p>
																		<p>
																			Too many stationery suppliers are often brides with no design background who've created their own stationery and decided to make a bit of money on the side creating stationery for others. </p>
																		<p>
																			Which leads me nicely onto...</p>




																													<div class="divider" style="margin-top:4em;margin-bottom:3em;"></div>

																													<h6 style="margin:0 auto;padding:0;">
												Substance is as important as style&hellip;
											</h6>


											<p>
												It's important for your invitations to look good: there's no doubt about that.</p>

											<p>
												But it's only half the battle: caught up in the delight of making sure everything looks perfect, it's very easy to forget that invitations serve a practical function too: to inform and educate your guests as much as possible about the event, and in turn,
												to make planning your wedding easier and therefore less stressful for you.

											</p>
											<p>

												To do that, you need to think of all the possible questions your guests are going to have and try to answer them in the content of your invitation.

											</p>
											<p>
												You're also going to need to figure out what information you're going to need back from them to help you plan your wedding, such as simple RSVPs for guest numbers and things like menu choices.

											</p>
											<p>
												Your guests are human, and like most humans, they're more likely to do something if it's easy and pain-free, so you also need to make it as easy as possible for them to reply.

											</p>
											<p>
												That's why those little extras, such as information enclosures and reply cards are important.

											</p>
											<p>
												A pre-addressed reply card increases your chances of getting responses quickly as it is very easy for your guests to just tick a box or two and post the card.

											</p>
											<p>
												We even print your guest names on the reply cards to make it even easier for them (and more accurate for you&mdash;leave it to your guests and believe me they won't even remember to write their own name so you won't know who the reply card is from!).

											</p>
											<p>
												No reply cards means no replies: and no replies means, among the other 101 things you need to do, you're going to have the hassle of chasing your guests to find out who is, or isn't, coming.

											</p>
											<p>
												In our experience, invitations with reply cards get around three times as many responses as invitations without!

											</p>
											<p>
												You'll find the number of details you provide about your wedding day is inversely proportional to the stress you'll experience (the more details you give, less stress for you!).

											</p>
											<p>
												That's why providing an additional instruction leaflet for all the extra stuff can really make your life easierso guests don't have to hassle you with questions at the last minute:

											</p>
											<p>
												Where exactly is the venue?

											</p>
											<p>
												A simple map can save you and your bridesmaids dealing with the exasperation of answering twenty phone calls on the morning of your wedding as lost guests phone you when they've gone up the wrong country lane.

											</p>
											<p>
												What do they wear?

											</p>
											<p>
												Explaining the dress code is important if you don't want Auntie Edna turning up in that bright puce dress with the ostentatious hat.

											</p>
											<p>
												Can children come?

											</p>
											<p>
												Can they give vouchers or money instead of buying you another garlic press?

											</p>
											<p>
												It's monotonous and rage-inducing to keep hearing the same questions again and again: avoid the bitterness by answering questions in advance with a comprehensive information enclosure.

											</p>

